FDA - Adverse Event Reporting System (FAERS) 
FOIA Case Report Information
was still present. He refused cares, removed peripheral venous accesses, naso-gastric tube and refused all oral 
food or drugs. On (b) (6) , control nuclear magnetic resonance imaging showed sub and supra-tentorial area 
with hypersignal T2-FLAIR compatible with lesions of progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy without 
associated contrast enhancement. A delayed signal anomaly, opposite the splenium of corpus callosum, was 
found, with a marked decrease of the apparent diffusion coefficient, initially described as atypical lesions of a 
progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy and more likely in favor of superadded cerebral lymphoma. Given 
patient's general status degradation, his neurological impairment with negative short-term prognosis, it was decided
not to start resuscitation. On(b) (6)  the patient was died. It was not known whether an autopsy was 
performed or not.
The health authority assessed the causal relationship of progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy as related with
mycophenolate mofetil, tacrolimus, prednisone and valganciclovir hydrochloride. 
The french imputability concerning the event progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy was Chronological 1, 
Semiological 2 and Imputability 1 for mycophenolate mofetil, tacrolimus and prednisone and was Chronological 1, 
Semiological 1 and Imputability 1 for valganciclovir hydrochloride. 
No further information was provided.